<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="604" pageId="6" pageNumber="603" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[160,1156,1530,1695]" lastBlockId="7.[160,1155,142,514]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="604" pageId="6" pageNumber="603">
<emphasis box="[160,338,1566,1591]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="603">Male and female</emphasis>
: About 
<quantity box="[425,502,1566,1591]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="6" pageNumber="603" unit="mm" value="11.0">11 mm</quantity>
in length. Head with black hairs mixed with short yellowish scaly hairs on the frons. Occiput with fine sparse whitish scaly hairs. Scutum and scutellum covered with black hairs, mixed with fine yellow-brown scaly hairs that become almost white at margins. Legs entirely black, covered with brownish scales. Wing pattern dimidiate, with basal half deeply infuscated black-brown, with a rather sharp outline. Clear area of wing with one or two small isolated spots, the outer one is more conspicuous and completely isolated, found on the origin of vein R4 (
<figureCitation box="[596,684,212,237]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="6.[160,225,1428,1451]" captionTargetBox="[174,1147,145,1394]" captionTargetId="figure-68@6.[166,1149,142,1396]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 2. Anthrax aygulus: (a) wing; (b) gonocoxites, ventral view; (c) hypopygium, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5477397" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5477397/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="604">Figure 2</figureCitation>
(a)). Plumula blackish. The outer margins of abdominal tergites 1‚Äì4 with tufts of black hairs, while those of anal tergites with shorter white hairs in addition to black bristles on the hind margins. Tergites 2‚Äì4 covered with numerous short yellow-brown scaly hairs. Tergites 1 and 2 with very narrow bands of white scaly hairs at hind margins. Tergites 5‚Äì7 entirely covered with white scales that are sparse and mixed with yellowish ones at middle of 5th and 6th tergites. Gonocoxites (
<figureCitation box="[1028,1119,385,410]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="6.[160,225,1428,1451]" captionTargetBox="[174,1147,145,1394]" captionTargetId="figure-68@6.[166,1149,142,1396]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 2. Anthrax aygulus: (a) wing; (b) gonocoxites, ventral view; (c) hypopygium, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5477397" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5477397/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="604">Figure 2</figureCitation>
(b)) quadratic, with two long apical prolongations or processes; epiphallus with complicated apical differentiations, with three short spines directed dorsally at apex and one spine before apex directed ventrally (
<figureCitation box="[505,595,489,514]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="6.[160,225,1428,1451]" captionTargetBox="[174,1147,145,1394]" captionTargetId="figure-68@6.[166,1149,142,1396]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 2. Anthrax aygulus: (a) wing; (b) gonocoxites, ventral view; (c) hypopygium, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5477397" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5477397/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="604">Figure 2</figureCitation>
(c)). Female genitalia could not be dissected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
